'''Macaquitos''' or '''Los Machaquitos''' is a [[slang]] and [[racist]] [[joke]] used by [[Argentines]] to reffer [[Brazilians]] in the [[Argentina and Brazil football rivalry]]. The intention is compare the [[mulato]] race in Brazil with [[monkey]]s.

The first time the word was quoted was in [[FIFA World Cup 1978]] when Brazil was considered the "moral winner" due to the controversy [[Referee (football)|referee]] arbitrations. The term popularized when brazilian journalists heard the offense in subsequent important games, such as [[FIFA World Cup 1982]] and [[FIFA World Cup 1986]]. In last decades, every Brazil x Argentina game the term is remembered in Brazil and quoted in Argentine newspapers to increase the nature of "war" of these games.

==1996==
In [[1996 Summer Olympics]], days before the Argentina know who is their next adversary in olympic football (Brazil or Nigeria) the Argentine newspaper [[Olé]] published the in the front page: "COME ON MONKEYS".

==2005==
In [[2005]] the term was quoted heavily in Argentine media due to three big fights: Brazil 1 vs. 3 Argentina (8/06) and Brazil 4 x 1 Argentina (29/6) and [[São Paulo Futebol Clube|São Paulo]] 2 x 0 [[Club Atlético River Plate|River Plate]] (22/06). Specially the incident with the player Grafite when Argentine [[Quilmes Atl%C3%A9tico Club|Quilmes]] player Leandro Desábato reacted with a racist insult towards Grafite.

==Other versions==
Many people in Brazil complain that the term is much older than football rivalry, being comming from the [[War of Paraguay]]. Old people says that Argentines imitated monkeys in stadiuns when Argentina played with Brazil in [[50s]]. 

